Quick recap/photo dump of 2022. It was a huge year of learning and growth, especially in areas outside of my 'career'.. Amazing how fast it went, and how quickly babies grow.

I set-out to be as present as possible in my daughters first year, and witness my wife be an amazing mother. Some of the most incredible things I've seen, and highest feelings I've felt in my life, happened in 2022, right here with them. I'm glad I was able to be home so much, and grateful for the career, team, and fans, that enable me that privilege.

So, 2022.. we got another dog. (Yep, 4 now). I spent more time with mates. I read books. I wrote and recorded a new album (ready for 2023). I graduated as a firefighter - a childhood dream i'd always sidelined, until now.

I did less hotels and planes, and more ute, and swag.
Went to the beach more.. Smoked a lot of brisket.

Got my shed put up. Every bloke needs a shed, right?

We took a little getaway to Fiji.

Squeezed in a stack of killer shows and festivals with the most amazing musicians (my band) and great fellas that are always a good laugh. I gave away 11 guitars, to people in the crowd. Mostly kids. Managed to buy myself a couple more keepers though.

After 2 years of pandemic downtime, into the past year of pretty easy going, I've never been so refreshed, rejuvenated or excited and ready to crank everything back up to full belt.

My heart is full. My hands and voice are ready to get back to work, and we will be bringing you a BIG couple years.. Can't wait to see ya' out there. '23, we're coming in hot.

Happy New Year everyone.
"Let's make it a good one, without any fear"

Love to all.
T

This time last year, Lismore and surrounds experienced one of the worst flooding natural disasters we've ever seen.. I was humbled and honoured to serve in some of the intense and extensive clean-up efforts - with @fireandrescuensw

Day after day, I saw the loss and devastation first hand, and even though it was right in front of my own eyes, it was STILL almost impossible to believe. In Lismore, Coraki, Woodburn, we shovelled mud, hosed out businesses, schools, helped gut shops, pile rubbish.. anything people needed or asked.

For all the unimaginable hardship around, and ahead, what really moved me, was the locals resilience to survive and rebuild, to come back better. 

This Saturday night, to mark 1 year since, I'm back in Lismore for 'Music From The Heart'. Playing a free concert in the CBD.. 

This time, I'm there for joy, celebration and raising a toast to the real heroes - the people of Lismore and surrounds.

It'll be an incredible night.

Love to all.

I don't see myself as a "guitar player"..
I'm more a singer who just likes to play a bit of guitar too.. I love the expression and release a guitar can give you - completely different to singing on its own. They speak emotions that words don't.

It's also a LOT of fun for me.

I get a lot of people ask about the variety of guitars.. and whilst I don't really own anything 'high end' or vintage to brag about.. I figured, if you're interested, I'll give a bit of info on them.. 

This guitar here is a straight of the shelf, Brad Paisley 'roadworn' Fender Telecaster (his signature model).. It's not an expensive guitar, but felt and sounded great excatly how it arrived, standard. Brad says it's a 'frankenstein' of his favourite features on several different fender telecasters, all put into his own model. 

The first gig I did with this guitar was @deniutemuster in 2019.. it's been a regular in my touring kit since..

Unlike other guitars of mine, it doesn't have a name.. just, Silver Tele.

Throwback to 'Call Me Crazy' at @deniutemuster 2019.

Wanna give a big, overdue and heartfelt shoutout to @matonguitars 

Maton are huge supporters of mine, and countless other Aussie musicians. They were the first people to put a professional instrument in my hands - right when I needed one, but also WAY before I could afford it.. 

The (now) beaten up, battered, yellowish-blonde guitar in slides 1 - 5 is my most loyal road companion. My Maton 808. It's been with me 19 years, and has never once left my touring arsenal. I'm so grateful for this guitar, and everything that's come from it - opportunities, songs, moments, rent money.. but mostly the inspiration to keep playing it. It's first outing with me was my (our) first ever @gympiemusicmuster in 2004. I nicknamed it 'workhorse', which it's proven to be, time and time again.

The guitar in slide 6 is a EBG808 'Nashville' model.. a completely different yet comfortably familiar beast. This came to me in 2011, on the eve of me opening a 20 date, national tour, for Rock n Roll queen @suziquatroreal - I fell madly in love with this guitar on that tour.. up there by myself every night to thousands of people, but feeling like I was holding a full-force band in my hands. I've called this guitar 'Suzi' ever since.

The guitar in the last slide might actually have the coolest story though.. It's an Australian Jumbo.. I became obsessed when I saw/heard @keithurban
using them on his 'Be Here' tour, 2006 (?)

I called Maton the day after his Enmore Theatre gig in Sydney, and said "I gotta have one", they said "we actually have 5 here right now for Keith to try out next week". I flew to Melbourne that day, played 'em all and took this one home.

It's a guitar built for Keith, that I beat him to. Haha. His amazing hands never got to touch it.. he can borrow it anytime though ;)

It's name is 'Yoink'.. like the noise in a cartoon when you steal something from someone. Haha.

Anyway, these guitars have been a huge part of me cutting a living, building a career, writing my songs.. or sometimes just kept me from losing my mind.

Sounds exaggerated, but I don't know where I'd be without these instruments, or Maton Guitars.

Australian made, for the world stage.
Love ya Maton..

Hey friends.. Travis here - I have decided to shift the release of my new album 'ANY LESS ANYMORE' a short skip and jump across to Jun 16th - just two weeks later..

There are actually several reasons for it, all very positive. I'll outline a couple :)

1. Pushing the release back just two weeks allows me the scheduling window to give you guys the track 'Raise Me' THIS FRIDAY on your streaming platforms. For me, it's the most special, personal, and vulnerable song on the record, and im so excited we get to give it the moment I feel it deserves. We've even shot a very touching video for this song - it's being edited right now and will be with you guys very soon. I can't wait for you to hear and see this one.

2. Your incredible and overwhelming support of the pre-orders through my website store means we've had to order more stock. CDs, Vinyl, and would you believe, Cassettes!! We'll need the extra couple weeks for everything to arrive and get all shipping sorted - remember, my wife and I do ALL of this dispatching ourselves whilst raising a 1 year old.

That's not a whinge, I actually love signing your orders, packing, and sending it personally - but this all takes a lot of time. I wanna do this release right by you (my fans) and for myself. The extra two weeks allow this.

3. I will be spending most of the original release weekend on planes, in vans, and out of service in remote WA. Making it very difficult to promote without being available/accessible to interviews, etc.

June 16th works MUCH better.

4. I have been working aaages on something SUPER, SUPER fkn cool to tie into this release, that despite our best efforts, won't be ready for you in time for the original release dates - but WILL be good to go for June 16th. more on that in coming days :)

5. Most importantly, on a personal level, this album 'Any Less Anymore' came from a place of me wanting to be better, do better.. As far as its release, June 16th gives me the opportunity to do it SO much better.

So, all pre-orders will be dispatched a few days before June 16th, so you'll hopefully have them on release day!!

Thank you for the love and understanding. Man, what a ride.

Let's do it. 🤟

'RAISE ME' out on streaming platforms this Friday, 19th May.

This song started as a letter to my unborn daughter when I was feeling pretty vulnerable, scared even, of not being ready or 'good enough'. These days, I feel invincible.

In our own way, we do a lot of growing up, too.. taking new steps, falling on our ass, getting back up. Its easy to get so lost in the beautiful, tired, crazy dance of raising a baby, that we often don't realise how much they're raising us.

The greatest thing I've EVER done, or been part of, is being a Dad. So, this one is for all the parents - the old, new, and especially those among us 'expecting' who just need to hear 'you got this', cos you actually have got this, and it's truly amazing 💪

Pre-Save and/or Pre-Add now
https://snd.click/RaiseMe

Love to all.
Trav
